# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lie-groups
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In mathematics, a **compact** (**topological**) **group** is a topological group whose topology realizes it as a compact topological space.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Compact groups are a natural generalization of finite groups with the discrete topology and have properties that carry over in significant fashion.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Compact groups have a well-understood theory, in relation to group actions and representation theory.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In the following we will assume all groups are Hausdorff spaces.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Lie groups form a class of topological groups, and the compact Lie groups have a particularly well-developed theory.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The classification theorem of compact Lie groups states that up to finite extensions and finite covers this exhausts the list of examples (which already includes some redundancies).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] This classification is described in more detail in the next subsection.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Any compact Lie group *G* has an identity component *G*0, defined as the connected component of the group in which the identity element lies.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The quotient group *G*/*G*0 is the group of components π0(*G*) which must be finite since *G* is compact.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] : Every connected compact Lie group is the quotient by a finite central subgroup of a product of a simply connected compact Lie group and a torus.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Thus, the classification of connected compact Lie groups can in principle be reduced to knowledge of the simply connected compact Lie groups together with information about their centers.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] or one of the five exceptional groups G2, F4, E6, E7, and E8.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The restrictions on *n* are to avoid special isomorphisms among the various families for small values of *n*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] For each of these groups, the center is known explicitly.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The classification is through the associated root system (for a fixed maximal torus), which in turn are classified by their Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The classification of compact, simply connected Lie groups is the same as the classification of complex semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Indeed, if *K* is a simply connected compact Lie group, then the complexification of the Lie algebra of *K* is semisimple.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Conversely, every complex semisimple Lie algebra has a compact real form isomorphic to the Lie algebra of a compact, simply connected Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A key idea in the study of a connected compact Lie group *K* is the concept of a *maximal torus*, that is a subgroup *T* of *K* that is isomorphic to a product of several copies of $S^{1}$ and that is not contained in any larger subgroup of this type.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A basic example is the case $K=\operatorname {SU} (n)$ , in which case we may take T to be the group of diagonal elements in K .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A basic result is the *torus theorem* which states that every element of K belongs to a maximal torus and that all maximal tori are conjugate.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The maximal torus in a compact group plays a role analogous to that of the Cartan subalgebra in a complex semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In particular, once a maximal torus $T\subset K$ has been chosen, one can define a root system and a Weyl group similar to what one has for semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] These structures then play an essential role both in the classification of connected compact groups (described above) and in the representation theory of a fixed such group (described below).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] It is important to know whether a connected compact Lie group is simply connected, and if not, to determine its fundamental group.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] For compact Lie groups, there are two basic approaches to computing the fundamental group.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The first approach applies to the classical compact groups $\operatorname {SU} (n)$ , $\operatorname {U} (n)$ , $\operatorname {SO} (n)$ , and $\operatorname {Sp} (n)$ and proceeds by induction on n .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The second approach uses the root system and applies to all connected compact Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] It is also important to know the center of a connected compact Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The center of a classical group G can easily be computed "by hand," and in most cases consists simply of whatever roots of the identity are in G .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] (The group SO(2) is an exception—the center is the whole group, even though most elements are not roots of the identity.) Thus, for example, the center of $\operatorname {SU} (n)$ consists of *n*th roots of unity times the identity, a cyclic group of order n .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In general, the center can be expressed in terms of the root lattice and the kernel of the exponential map for the maximal torus.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The general method shows, for example, that the simply connected compact group corresponding to the exceptional root system $G_{2}$ has trivial center.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Thus, the compact $G_{2}$ group is one of very few simple compact groups that are simultaneously simply connected and center free.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Amongst groups that are not Lie groups, and so do not carry the structure of a manifold, examples are the additive group *Z**p* of p-adic integers, and constructions from it.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In fact any profinite group is a compact group.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] This means that Galois groups are compact groups, a basic fact for the theory of algebraic extensions in the case of infinite degree.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Pontryagin duality provides a large supply of examples of compact commutative groups.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] These are in duality with abelian discrete groups.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Compact groups all carry a Haar measure, which will be invariant by both left and right translation (the modulus function must be a continuous homomorphism to positive reals (**R**+, ×), and so 1).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In other words, these groups are unimodular.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Haar measure is easily normalized to be a probability measure, analogous to dθ/2π on the circle.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Such a Haar measure is in many cases easy to compute; for example for orthogonal groups it was known to Adolf Hurwitz, and in the Lie group cases can always be given by an invariant differential form.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In the profinite case there are many subgroups of finite index, and Haar measure of a coset will be the reciprocal of the index.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Therefore, integrals are often computable quite directly, a fact applied constantly in number theory.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] If K is a compact group and m is the associated Haar measure, the Peter–Weyl theorem provides a decomposition of $L^{2}(K,dm)$ as an orthogonal direct sum of finite-dimensional subspaces of matrix entries for the irreducible representations of K .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The representation theory of compact groups (not necessarily Lie groups and not necessarily connected) was founded by the Peter–Weyl theorem.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Hermann Weyl went on to give the detailed character theory of the compact connected Lie groups, based on maximal torus theory.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The resulting Weyl character formula was one of the influential results of twentieth century mathematics.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The combination of the Peter–Weyl theorem and the Weyl character formula led Weyl to a complete classification of the representations of a connected compact Lie group; this theory is described in the next section.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A combination of Weyl's work and Cartan's theorem gives a survey of the whole representation theory of compact groups *G*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] That is, by the Peter–Weyl theorem the irreducible unitary representations ρ of *G* are into a unitary group (of finite dimension) and the image will be a closed subgroup of the unitary group by compactness.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Cartan's theorem states that Im(ρ) must itself be a Lie subgroup in the unitary group.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] If *G* is not itself a Lie group, there must be a kernel to ρ.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Further one can form an inverse system, for the kernel of ρ smaller and smaller, of finite-dimensional unitary representations, which identifies *G* as an inverse limit of compact Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Here the fact that in the limit a faithful representation of *G* is found is another consequence of the Peter–Weyl theorem.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The unknown part of the representation theory of compact groups is thereby, roughly speaking, thrown back onto the complex representations of finite groups.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] This theory is rather rich in detail, but is qualitatively well understood.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Certain simple examples of the representation theory of compact Lie groups can be worked out by hand, such as the representations of the rotation group SO(3), the special unitary group SU(2), and the special unitary group SU(3).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] See also the parallel theory of representations of a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Throughout this section, we fix a connected compact Lie group *K* and a maximal torus *T* in *K*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Since, also, *T* is compact, $\rho$ must actually map into $S^{1}\subset \mathbb {C}$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] for some linear functional $\lambda$ on ${\mathfrak {t}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Now, since the exponential map $H\mapsto e^{H}$ is not injective, not every such linear functional $\lambda$ gives rise to a well-defined map of *T* into $S^{1}$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] where $\operatorname {Id}$ is the identity element of *T*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] where $\mathbb {Z}$ is the set of integers.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A linear functional $\lambda$ satisfying this condition is called an **analytically integral element**.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] This integrality condition is related to, but not identical to, the notion of integral element in the setting of semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Suppose, for example, *T* is just the group $S^{1}$ of complex numbers $e^{i\theta }$ of absolute value 1.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The Lie algebra is the set of purely imaginary numbers, $H=i\theta ,\,\theta \in \mathbb {R} ,$ and the kernel of the (scaled) exponential map is the set of numbers of the form $in$ where n is an integer.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A linear functional $\lambda$ takes integer values on all such numbers if and only if it is of the form $\lambda (i\theta )=k\theta$ for some integer k .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We now let $\Sigma$ denote a finite-dimensional irreducible representation of *K* (over $\mathbb {C}$ ).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We then consider the restriction of $\Sigma$ to *T*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] This restriction is not irreducible unless $\Sigma$ is one-dimensional.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Nevertheless, the restriction decomposes as a direct sum of irreducible representations of *T*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] (Note that a given irreducible representation of *T* may occur more than once.) Now, each irreducible representation of *T* is described by a linear functional $\lambda$ as in the preceding subsection.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] If a given $\lambda$ occurs at least once in the decomposition of the restriction of $\Sigma$ to *T*, we call $\lambda$ a **weight** of $\Sigma$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The strategy of the representation theory of *K* is to classify the irreducible representations in terms of their weights.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We now briefly describe the structures needed to formulate the theorem; more details can be found in the article on weights in representation theory.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We need the notion of a **root system** for *K* (relative to a given maximal torus *T*).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The construction of this root system $R\subset {\mathfrak {t}}$ is very similar to the construction for complex semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Specifically, the weights are the nonzero weights for the adjoint action of *T* on the complexified Lie algebra of *K*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The root system *R* has all the usual properties of a root system, except that the elements of *R* may not span ${\mathfrak {t}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We then choose a base $\Delta$ for *R* and we say that an integral element $\lambda$ is **dominant** if $\lambda (\alpha )\geq 0$ for all $\alpha \in \Delta$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Finally, we say that one weight is **higher** than another if their difference can be expressed as a linear combination of elements of $\Delta$ with non-negative coefficients.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The irreducible finite-dimensional representations of *K* are then classified by a **theorem of the highest weight**, which is closely related to the analogous theorem classifying representations of a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] 4. every dominant, analytically integral element arises as the highest weight of an irreducible representation.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The theorem of the highest weight for representations of *K* is then almost the same as for semisimple Lie algebras, with one notable exception: The concept of an integral element is different.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The weights $\lambda$ of a representation $\Sigma$ are analytically integral in the sense described in the previous subsection.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Every analytically integral element is integral in the Lie algebra sense, but not the other way around.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] This function is easily seen to be a class function, i.e., $\mathrm {X} (xyx^{-1})=\mathrm {X} (y)$ for all x and y in *K*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Thus, $\mathrm {X}$ is determined by its restriction to *T*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The study of characters is an important part of the representation theory of compact groups.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] One crucial result, which is a corollary of the Peter–Weyl theorem, is that the characters form an orthonormal basis for the set of square-integrable class functions in *K*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] A second key result is the Weyl character formula, which gives an explicit formula for the character—or, rather, the restriction of the character to *T*—in terms of the highest weight of the representation.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In the closely related representation theory of semisimple Lie algebras, the Weyl character formula is an additional result established *after* the representations have been classified.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In Weyl's analysis of the compact group case, however, the Weyl character formula is actually a crucial part of the classification itself.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] In Weyl's approach, the construction is based on the Peter–Weyl theorem and an analytic proof of the Weyl character formula.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Ultimately, the irreducible representations of *K* are realized inside the space of continuous functions on *K*.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We now consider the case of the compact group SU(2).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The representations are often considered from the Lie algebra point of view, but we here look at them from the group point of view.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] According to the example discussed above in the section on representations of *T*, the analytically integral elements are labeled by integers, so that the dominant, analytically integral elements are non-negative integers m .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The general theory then tells us that for each m , there is a unique irreducible representation of SU(2) with highest weight m .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Much information about the representation corresponding to a given m is encoded in its character.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] (The weights are the integers appearing in the exponents of the exponentials and the multiplicities are the coefficients of the exponentials.) Since there are $m+1$ weights, each with multiplicity 1, the dimension of the representation is $m+1$ .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Thus, we recover much of the information about the representations that is usually obtained from the Lie algebra computation.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We now outline the proof of the theorem of the highest weight, following the original argument of Hermann Weyl.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We continue to let K be a connected compact Lie group and T a fixed maximal torus in K .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We focus on the most difficult part of the theorem, showing that every dominant, analytically integral element is the highest weight of some (finite-dimensional) irreducible representation.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] With these tools in hand, we proceed with the proof.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The first major step in the argument is to prove the Weyl character formula.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Here $\rho$ is half the sum of the positive roots.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] (The notation uses the convention of "real weights"; this convention requires an explicit factor of i in the exponent.) Weyl's proof of the character formula is analytic in nature and hinges on the fact that the $L^{2}$ norm of the character is 1.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Specifically, if there were any additional terms in the numerator, the Weyl integral formula would force the norm of the character to be greater than 1.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Next, we let $\Phi _{\lambda }$ denote the function on the right-hand side of the character formula.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We show that *even if $\lambda$ is not known to be the highest weight of a representation*, $\Phi _{\lambda }$ is a well-defined, Weyl-invariant function on T , which therefore extends to a class function on K .
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Then using the Weyl integral formula, one can show that as $\lambda$ ranges over the set of dominant, analytically integral elements, the functions $\Phi _{\lambda }$ form an orthonormal family of class functions.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] We emphasize that we do not currently know that every such $\lambda$ is the highest weight of a representation; nevertheless, the expressions on the right-hand side of the character formula gives a well-defined set of functions $\Phi _{\lambda }$ , and these functions are orthonormal.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The set of all $\Phi _{\lambda }$ —with $\lambda$ ranging over the dominant, analytically integral elements—forms an orthonormal set in the space of square integrable class functions.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] But by the Weyl character formula, the characters of the irreducible representations form a subset of the $\Phi _{\lambda }$ 's.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] And by the Peter–Weyl theorem, the characters of the irreducible representations form an orthonormal basis for the space of square integrable class functions.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] If there were some $\lambda$ that is not the highest weight of a representation, then the corresponding $\Phi _{\lambda }$ would not be the character of a representation.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Thus, the characters would be a *proper* subset of the set of $\Phi _{\lambda }$ 's.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] But then we have an impossible situation: an orthonormal *basis* (the set of characters of the irreducible representations) would be contained in a strictly larger orthonormal set (the set of $\Phi _{\lambda }$ 's).
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Thus, every $\lambda$ must actually be the highest weight of a representation.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The topic of recovering a compact group from its representation theory is the subject of the Tannaka–Krein duality, now often recast in terms of Tannakian category theory.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] The influence of the compact group theory on non-compact groups was formulated by Weyl in his unitarian trick.
[src:lie-groups/compact-group] Inside a general semisimple Lie group there is a maximal compact subgroup, and the representation theory of such groups, developed largely by Harish-Chandra, uses intensively the restriction of a representation to such a subgroup, and also the model of Weyl's character theory.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In the mathematical field of Lie theory, a **Dynkin diagram**, named for Eugene Dynkin, is a type of graph with some edges doubled or tripled (drawn as a double or triple line).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams arise in the classification of semisimple Lie algebras over algebraically closed fields, in the classification of Weyl groups and other finite reflection groups, and in other contexts.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Various properties of the Dynkin diagram (such as whether it contains multiple edges, or its symmetries) correspond to important features of the associated Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The term "Dynkin diagram" can be ambiguous.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In some cases, Dynkin diagrams are assumed to be directed, in which case they correspond to root systems and semi-simple Lie algebras, while in other cases they are assumed to be undirected, in which case they correspond to Weyl groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In this article, "Dynkin diagram" means *directed* Dynkin diagram, and *undirected* Dynkin diagrams will be explicitly so named.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The fundamental interest in Dynkin diagrams is that they classify semisimple Lie algebras over algebraically closed fields.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] One classifies such Lie algebras via their root system, which can be represented by a Dynkin diagram.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] One then classifies Dynkin diagrams according to the constraints they must satisfy, as described below.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dropping the direction on the graph edges corresponds to replacing a root system by the finite reflection group it generates, the so-called Weyl group, and thus undirected Dynkin diagrams classify Weyl groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For the exceptional groups, the names for the Lie algebra and the associated Dynkin diagram coincide.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams can be interpreted as classifying many distinct, related objects, and the notation "A*n*, B*n*, ..." is used to refer to *all* such interpretations, depending on context; this ambiguity can be confusing.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The central classification is that a simple Lie algebra has a root system, to which is associated an (oriented) Dynkin diagram; all three of these may be referred to as B*n*, for instance.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The *un*oriented Dynkin diagram is a form of Coxeter diagram, and corresponds to the Weyl group, which is the finite reflection group associated to the root system.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Thus B*n* may refer to the unoriented diagram (a special kind of Coxeter diagram), the Weyl group (a concrete reflection group), or the abstract Coxeter group.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Although the Weyl group is abstractly isomorphic to the Coxeter group, a specific isomorphism depends on an ordered choice of simple roots.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Likewise, while Dynkin diagram notation is standardized, Coxeter diagram and group notation is varied and sometimes agrees with Dynkin diagram notation and sometimes does not.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Lastly, *sometimes* associated objects are referred to by the same notation, though this cannot always be done regularly.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] These latter notations are mostly used for objects associated with exceptional diagrams – objects associated to the regular diagrams (A, B, C, D) instead have traditional names.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The index (the *n*) is the number of nodes in the diagram, the number of simple roots in a basis, the dimension of the root lattice and span of the root system, the number of generators of the Coxeter group, and the rank of the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] However, *n* does not equal the dimension of the defining module (a fundamental representation) of the Lie algebra – the index on the Dynkin diagram should not be confused with the index on the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For example, $B_{4}$ corresponds to ${\mathfrak {so}}_{2\cdot 4+1}={\mathfrak {so}}_{9},$ which naturally acts on 9-dimensional space, but has rank 4 as a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The simply laced Dynkin diagrams, those with no multiple edges (A, D, E) classify many further mathematical objects; see discussion at ADE classification.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Consider a root system, assumed to be reduced and integral (or "crystallographic").
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In many applications, this root system will arise from a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Let $\Delta$ be a set of positive simple roots.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] We then construct a diagram from $\Delta$ as follows.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Form a graph with one vertex for each element of $\Delta$ .
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Then insert edges between each pair of vertices according to the following recipe.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] If the roots corresponding to the two vertices are orthogonal, there is no edge between the vertices.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] If the angle between the two roots is 120 degrees, we put one edge between the vertices.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] If the angle is 135 degrees, we put two edges, and if the angle is 150 degrees, we put three edges.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] (These four cases exhaust all possible angles between pairs of positive simple roots.) Finally, if there are any edges between a given pair of vertices, we decorate them with an arrow pointing from the vertex corresponding to the longer root to the vertex corresponding to the shorter one.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] (The arrow is omitted if the roots have the same length.) Thinking of the arrow as a "greater than" sign makes it clear which way the arrow should go.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams lead to a classification of root systems.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The angles and length ratios between roots are related.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Thus, the edges for non-orthogonal roots may alternatively be described as one edge for a length ratio of 1, two edges for a length ratio of ${\sqrt {2}}$ , and three edges for a length ratio of ${\sqrt {3}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In the $A_{2}$ root system, shown at right, the roots labeled $\alpha$ and $\beta$ form a base.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Since these two roots are at angle of 120 degrees (with a length ratio of 1), the Dynkin diagram consists of two vertices connected by a single edge: .
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams are closely related to Coxeter diagrams of finite Coxeter groups, and the terminology is often conflated.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] data than the underlying Coxeter diagram (undirected graph).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] At the level of root systems the direction corresponds to pointing towards the shorter vector; edges labeled "3" have no direction because the corresponding vectors must have equal length.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams must satisfy an additional restriction, namely that the only allowable edge labels are 2, 3, 4, and 6, a restriction not shared by Coxeter diagrams, so not every Coxeter diagram of a finite group comes from a Dynkin diagram.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] A further difference, which is only stylistic, is that Dynkin diagrams are conventionally drawn with double or triple edges between nodes (for *p* = 4, 6), rather than an edge labeled with "*p*".
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The term "Dynkin diagram" at times refers to the *directed* graph, at times to the *undirected* graph.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For precision, in this article "Dynkin diagram" will mean *directed,* and the underlying undirected graph will be called an "undirected Dynkin diagram".
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The blank in the upper right, corresponding to directed graphs with underlying undirected graph any Coxeter diagram (of a finite group), can be defined formally, but is little-discussed, and does not appear to admit a simple interpretation in terms of mathematical objects of interest.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] There are natural maps down – from Dynkin diagrams to undirected Dynkin diagrams; respectively, from root systems to the associated Weyl groups – and right – from undirected Dynkin diagrams to Coxeter diagrams; respectively from Weyl groups to finite Coxeter groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The down map is onto (by definition) but not one-to-one, as the *B**n* and *C**n* diagrams map to the same undirected diagram, with the resulting Coxeter diagram and Weyl group thus sometimes denoted *BC**n*.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Trivially, one can start the families at $n=0$ or $n=1,$ which are all then isomorphic as there is a unique empty diagram and a unique 1-node diagram.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] These isomorphisms correspond to isomorphism of simple and semisimple Lie algebras, which also correspond to certain isomorphisms of Lie group forms of these.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In addition to isomorphism between different diagrams, some diagrams also have self-isomorphisms or "automorphisms".
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Diagram automorphisms correspond to outer automorphisms of the Lie algebra, meaning that the outer automorphism group Out = Aut/Inn equals the group of diagram automorphisms.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The diagrams that have non-trivial automorphisms are A*n* ( $n>1$ ), D*n* ( $n>1$ ), and E6.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In all these cases except for D4, there is a single non-trivial automorphism (Out = *C*2, the cyclic group of order 2), while for D4, the automorphism group is the symmetric group on three letters (*S*3, order 6) – this phenomenon is known as "triality".
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] It happens that all these diagram automorphisms can be realized as Euclidean symmetries of how the diagrams are conventionally drawn in the plane, but this is just an artifact of how they are drawn, and not intrinsic structure.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For A*n*, the diagram automorphism is reversing the diagram, which is a line.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For D*n*, the diagram automorphism is switching the two nodes at the end of the Y, and corresponds to switching the two chiral spin representations.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Realized as the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {so}}_{2n},$ the outer automorphism can be expressed as conjugation by a matrix in O(2*n*) with determinant −1.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] When *n* = 3, one has $\mathrm {D} _{3}\cong \mathrm {A} _{3},$ so their automorphisms agree, while $\mathrm {D} _{2}\cong \mathrm {A} _{1}\times \mathrm {A} _{1}$ is disconnected, and the automorphism corresponds to switching the two nodes.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For D4, the fundamental representation is isomorphic to the two spin representations, and the resulting symmetric group on three letter (*S*3, or alternatively the dihedral group of order 6, Dih3) corresponds both to automorphisms of the Lie algebra and automorphisms of the diagram.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The automorphism group of E6 corresponds to reversing the diagram, and can be expressed using Jordan algebras.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Disconnected diagrams, which correspond to *semi*simple Lie algebras, may have automorphisms from exchanging components of the diagram.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In positive characteristic there are additional "diagram automorphisms" – roughly speaking, in characteristic *p* one is sometimes allowed to ignore the arrow on bonds of multiplicity *p* in the Dynkin diagram when taking diagram automorphisms.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Thus in characteristic 2 there is an order 2 automorphism of $\mathrm {B} _{2}\cong \mathrm {C} _{2}$ and of F4, while in characteristic 3 there is an order 2 automorphism of G2.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] But doesn't apply in all circumstances: for example, such automorphisms need not arise as automorphisms of the corresponding algebraic group, but rather on the level of points valued in a finite field.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Diagram automorphisms in turn yield additional Lie groups and groups of Lie type, which are of central importance in the classification of finite simple groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The Chevalley group construction of Lie groups in terms of their Dynkin diagram does not yield some of the classical groups, namely the unitary groups and the non-split orthogonal groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The Steinberg groups construct the unitary groups 2A*n*, while the other orthogonal groups are constructed as 2D*n*, where in both cases this refers to combining a diagram automorphism with a field automorphism.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] This also yields additional exotic Lie groups 2E6 and 3D4, the latter only defined over fields with an order 3 automorphism.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The additional diagram automorphisms in positive characteristic yield the Suzuki–Ree groups, 2B2, 2F4, and 2G2.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] A (simply-laced) Dynkin diagram (finite or affine) that has a symmetry (satisfying one condition, below) can be quotiented by the symmetry, yielding a new, generally multiply laced diagram, with the process called **folding** (due to most symmetries being 2-fold).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] At the level of Lie algebras, this corresponds to taking the invariant subalgebra under the outer automorphism group, and the process can be defined purely with reference to root systems, without using diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Further, every multiply laced diagram (finite or infinite) can be obtained by folding a simply-laced diagram.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The one condition on the automorphism for folding to be possible is that distinct nodes of the graph in the same orbit (under the automorphism) must not be connected by an edge; at the level of root systems, roots in the same orbit must be orthogonal.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] At the level of diagrams, this is necessary as otherwise the quotient diagram will have a loop, due to identifying two nodes but having an edge between them, and loops are not allowed in Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For example, in D4 folding to G2, the edge in G2 points from the class of the 3 outer nodes (valence 1), to the class of the central node (valence 3).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The notion of foldings can also be applied more generally to Coxeter diagrams – notably, one can generalize allowable quotients of Dynkin diagrams to Hn and I2(*p*).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Geometrically this corresponds to projections of uniform polytopes.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Notably, any simply laced Dynkin diagram can be folded to I2(*h*), where *h* is the Coxeter number, which corresponds geometrically to projection to the Coxeter plane.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Folding can be applied to reduce questions about (semisimple) Lie algebras to questions about simply-laced ones, together with an automorphism, which may be simpler than treating multiply laced algebras directly; this can be done in constructing the semisimple Lie algebras, for instance.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] See Math Overflow: Folding by Automorphisms for further discussion.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Some additional maps of diagrams have meaningful interpretations, as detailed below.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] However, not all maps of root systems arise as maps of diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For example, there are two inclusions of root systems of A2 in G2, either as the six long roots or the six short roots.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] However, the nodes in the G2 diagram correspond to one long root and one short root, while the nodes in the A2 diagram correspond to roots of equal length, and thus this map of root systems cannot be expressed as a map of the diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Some inclusions of root systems can be expressed as one diagram being an induced subgraph of another, meaning "a subset of the nodes, with all edges between them".
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] This is because eliminating a node from a Dynkin diagram corresponds to removing a simple root from a root system, which yields a root system of rank one lower.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] By contrast, removing an edge (or changing the multiplicity of an edge) while leaving the nodes unchanged corresponds to changing the angles between roots, which cannot be done without changing the entire root system.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Thus, one can meaningfully remove nodes, but not edges.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Removing a node from a connected diagram may yield a connected diagram (simple Lie algebra), if the node is a leaf, or a disconnected diagram (semisimple but not simple Lie algebra), with either two or three components (the latter for D*n* and E*n*).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] At the level of Lie algebras, these inclusions correspond to sub-Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Finally, duality of diagrams corresponds to reversing the direction of arrows, if any: Bn and Cn are dual, while F4, and G2 are self-dual, as are the simply-laced ADE diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] A Dynkin diagram with no multiple edges is called **simply laced**, as are the corresponding Lie algebra and Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] These are the $A_{n},D_{n},E_{n}$ diagrams, and phenomena that such diagrams classify are referred to as an ADE classification.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In this case the Dynkin diagrams exactly coincide with Coxeter diagrams, as there are no multiple edges.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams classify *complex* semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams are named for Eugene Dynkin, who used them in two papers (1946, 1947) simplifying the classification of semisimple Lie algebras; see (Dynkin 2000).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] When Dynkin left the Soviet Union in 1976, which was at the time considered tantamount to treason, Soviet mathematicians were directed to refer to "diagrams of simple roots" rather than use his name.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin then used them in 1946 and 1947, acknowledging Coxeter and Witt in his 1947 paper.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Beyond simplicity, a further benefit of this convention is that diagram automorphisms are realized by Euclidean isometries of the diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Alternative convention include writing a number by the edge to indicate multiplicity (commonly used in Coxeter diagrams), darkening nodes to indicate root length, or using 120° angles on valence 2 nodes to make the nodes more distinct.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] There are also conventions about numbering the nodes.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The most common modern convention had developed by the 1960s and is illustrated in (Bourbaki 1968).
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Dynkin diagrams are equivalent to generalized Cartan matrices, as shown in this table of rank 2 Dynkin diagrams with their corresponding 2 × 2 Cartan matrices.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] A multi-edged diagram corresponds to the nondiagonal Cartan matrix elements ⁠ $-a_{21},-a_{12}$ ⁠, with the number of edges drawn equal to ⁠ $\max(-a_{21},-a_{12})$ ⁠, and an arrow pointing towards nonunity elements.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For non-diagonal entries, $a_{ij}\leq 0$ .
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The Cartan matrix determines whether the group is of **finite type** (if it is a positive-definite matrix, i.e. all eigenvalues are positive), of **affine type** (if it is not positive-definite but positive-semidefinite, i.e. all eigenvalues are non-negative), or of **indefinite type**.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The indefinite type often is further subdivided, for example a Coxeter group is **Lorentzian** if it has one negative eigenvalue and all other eigenvalues are positive.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Moreover, multiple sources refer to **hyberbolic** Coxeter groups, but there are several non-equivalent definitions for this term.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] In the discussion below, hyperbolic Coxeter groups are a special case of Lorentzian, satisfying an extra condition.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] For rank 2, all negative determinant Cartan matrices correspond to hyperbolic Coxeter group.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] But in general, most negative determinant matrices are neither hyperbolic nor Lorentzian.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] There are extensions of Dynkin diagrams, namely the **affine Dynkin diagrams**; these classify Cartan matrices of affine Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] These are classified in (Kac 1994, Chapter 4, pp.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] 47–), specifically listed on (Kac 1994, pp.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Affine diagrams are denoted as $X_{l}^{(1)},X_{l}^{(2)},$ or $X_{l}^{(3)},$ where *X* is the letter of the corresponding finite diagram, and the exponent depends on which series of affine diagrams they are in.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The first of these, $X_{l}^{(1)},$ are most common, and are called **extended Dynkin diagrams** and denoted with a tilde, and also sometimes marked with a **+** superscript. as in ${\tilde {A}}_{5}=A_{5}^{(1)}=A_{5}^{+}$ .
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The (2) and (3) series are called **twisted affine diagrams**.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] See Dynkin diagram generator for diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Here are all of the Dynkin graphs for affine groups up to 10 nodes.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Extended Dynkin graphs are given as the *~* families, the same as the finite graphs above, with one node added.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Other directed-graph variations are given with a superscript value (2) or (3), representing foldings of higher order groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] These are categorized as *Twisted affine* diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The set of compact and noncompact hyperbolic Dynkin graphs has been enumerated.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] All rank 3 hyperbolic graphs are compact.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Compact hyperbolic Dynkin diagrams exist up to rank 5, and noncompact hyperbolic graphs exist up to rank 10.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Some notations used in theoretical physics, such as M-theory, use a "+" superscript for extended groups instead of a "~" and this allows higher extensions groups to be defined.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] **Over-extended** Dynkin diagrams (hyperbolic) are given "^" or "++" and represent two added nodes.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] **Very-extended** Dynkin diagrams with 3 nodes added are given "+++".
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The 238 hyperbolic groups (compact and noncompact) of rank $n\geq 3$ are named as $H_{i}^{(n)}$ and listed as $i=1,2,3...$ for each rank.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Very-extended groups are Lorentz groups, defined by adding three nodes to the finite groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The E8, E7, E6, F4, and G2 offer six series ending as very-extended groups.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] Other extended series not shown can be defined from An, Bn, Cn, and Dn, as different series for each *n*.
[src:lie-groups/dynkin-diagram] The determinant of the associated Cartan matrix determine where the series changes from finite (positive) to affine (zero) to a noncompact hyperbolic group (negative), and ending as a Lorentz group that can be defined with the use of one time-like dimension, and is used in M theory.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] In the theory of Lie groups, the **exponential map** is a map from the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ of a Lie group G to the group, which allows one to recapture the local group structure from the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The existence of the exponential map is one of the primary reasons that Lie algebras are a useful tool for studying Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The ordinary exponential function of mathematical analysis is a special case of the exponential map when G is the multiplicative group of positive real numbers (whose Lie algebra is the additive group of all real numbers).
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The exponential map of a Lie group satisfies many properties analogous to those of the ordinary exponential function, however, it also differs in many important respects.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Let G be a Lie group and ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be its Lie algebra (thought of as the tangent space to the identity element of G ).
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] which can be defined in several different ways.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] It follows easily from the chain rule that $\exp(tX)=\gamma (t)$ .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The map $\gamma$ , a group homomorphism from $(\mathbb {R} ,+)$ to G , may be constructed as the integral curve of either the right- or left-invariant vector field associated with X .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] That the integral curve exists for all real parameters follows by right- or left-translating the solution near zero.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] We have a more concrete definition in the case of a matrix Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Thus, in the setting of matrix Lie groups, the exponential map is the restriction of the matrix exponential to the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ of G .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] If *G* is compact, it has a Riemannian metric invariant under left *and* right translations, then the Lie-theoretic exponential map for *G* coincides with the exponential map of this Riemannian metric.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] For a general *G*, there will not exist a Riemannian metric invariant under both left and right translations.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Although there is always a Riemannian metric invariant under, say, left translations, the exponential map in the sense of Riemannian geometry for a left-invariant metric will *not* in general agree with the exponential map in the Lie group sense.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] That is to say, if *G* is a Lie group equipped with a left- but not right-invariant metric, the geodesics through the identity will not be one-parameter subgroups of *G*.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] corresponds to the exponential map for the complex Lie group X .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Compare this to the first example above.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] For all $X\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ , the map $\gamma (t)=\exp(tX)$ is the unique one-parameter subgroup of G whose tangent vector at the identity is X .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The preceding identity does not hold in general; the assumption that X and Y commute is important.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The image of the exponential map always lies in the identity component of G .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The exponential map $\exp \colon {\mathfrak {g}}\to G$ is a smooth map.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Its differential at zero, $\exp _{*}\colon {\mathfrak {g}}\to {\mathfrak {g}}$ , is the identity map (with the usual identifications).
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] It follows from the inverse function theorem that the exponential map, therefore, restricts to a diffeomorphism from some neighborhood of 0 in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ to a neighborhood of 1 in G .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] It is then not difficult to show that if *G* is connected, every element *g* of *G* is a *product* of exponentials of elements of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ : $g=\exp(X_{1})\exp(X_{2})\cdots \exp(X_{n}),\quad X_{j}\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Globally, the exponential map is not necessarily surjective.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Furthermore, the exponential map may not be a local diffeomorphism at all points.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] For example, the exponential map from ${\mathfrak {so}}$ (3) to SO(3) is not a local diffeomorphism; see also cut locus on this failure.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] See derivative of the exponential map for more information.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] For groups not satisfying any of the above conditions, the exponential map may or may not be surjective.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] The image of the exponential map of the connected but non-compact group *SL*2(**R**) is not the whole group.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Its image consists of $\mathbb {C}$ -diagonalizable matrices with eigenvalues either positive or with modulus 1 , and of non-diagonalizable matrices with a repeated eigenvalue 1 , and the matrix $-I$ .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Let $\phi \colon G\to H$ be a Lie group homomorphism and let $\phi _{*}$ be its derivative at the identity.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Given a Lie group G with Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , each choice of a basis $X_{1},\dots ,X_{n}$ of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ determines a coordinate system near the identity element e for G , as follows.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] By the inverse function theorem, the exponential map $\exp :N\xrightarrow {\sim } U$ is a diffeomorphism from some neighborhood $N\subset {\mathfrak {g}}\simeq \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ of the origin to a neighborhood U of $e\in G$ .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] Its inverse: $\log :U\xrightarrow {\sim } N\subset \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is then a coordinate system on U .
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] It is called by various names such as logarithmic coordinates, exponential coordinates or normal coordinates.
[src:lie-groups/exponential-map-lie-theory] See the closed-subgroup theorem for an example of how they are used in applications.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In mathematics, a **Lie group** (pronounced /liː/ *Lee*) is a group that is also a differentiable manifold, such that group multiplication and taking inverses are both differentiable.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Combining these two ideas, one obtains a continuous group where multiplying points and their inverses is continuous.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] If the multiplication and taking of inverses are smooth (differentiable) as well, one obtains a Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups provide a natural model for the concept of continuous symmetry, a celebrated example of which is the circle group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Rotating a circle is an example of a continuous symmetry.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] For any rotation of the circle, there exists the same symmetry, and concatenation of such rotations makes them into the circle group, an archetypal example of a Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups are widely used in many parts of modern mathematics and physics.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups were first found by studying matrix subgroups G contained in ${\text{GL}}_{n}(\mathbb {R} )$ or ⁠ ${\text{GL}}_{n}(\mathbb {C} )$ ⁠, the groups of $n\times n$ invertible matrices over $\mathbb {R}$ or ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] These are now called the classical groups, as the concept has been extended far beyond these origins.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups are named after Norwegian mathematician Sophus Lie (1842–1899), who laid the foundations of the theory of continuous transformation groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie's original motivation for introducing Lie groups was to model the continuous symmetries of differential equations, in much the same way that finite groups are used in Galois theory to model the discrete symmetries of algebraic equations.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Sophus Lie considered the winter of 1873–1874 as the birth date of his theory of continuous groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Thomas Hawkins, however, suggests that it was "Lie's prodigious research activity during the four-year period from the fall of 1869 to the fall of 1873" that led to the theory's creation.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Some of Lie's early ideas were developed in close collaboration with Felix Klein.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie met with Klein every day from October 1869 through 1872: in Berlin from the end of October 1869 to the end of February 1870, and in Paris, Göttingen and Erlangen in the subsequent two years.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie stated that all of the principal results were obtained by 1884.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] But during the 1870s all his papers (except the very first note) were published in Norwegian journals, which impeded recognition of the work throughout the rest of Europe.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In 1884 a young German mathematician, Friedrich Engel, came to work with Lie on a systematic treatise to expose his theory of continuous groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] From this effort resulted the three-volume *Theorie der Transformationsgruppen*, published in 1888, 1890, and 1893.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The term *groupes de Lie* first appeared in French in 1893 in the thesis of Lie's student Arthur Tresse.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie's ideas did not stand in isolation from the rest of mathematics.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In fact, his interest in the geometry of differential equations was first motivated by the work of Carl Gustav Jacobi, on the theory of partial differential equations of first order and on the equations of classical mechanics.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Much of Jacobi's work was published posthumously in the 1860s, generating enormous interest in France and Germany.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie's *idée fixe* was to develop a theory of symmetries of differential equations that would accomplish for them what Évariste Galois had done for algebraic equations: namely, to classify them in terms of group theory.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie and other mathematicians showed that the most important equations for special functions and orthogonal polynomials tend to arise from group theoretical symmetries.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In Lie's early work, the idea was to construct a theory of *continuous groups*, to complement the theory of discrete groups that had developed in the theory of modular forms, in the hands of Felix Klein and Henri Poincaré.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The initial application that Lie had in mind was to the theory of differential equations.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] On the model of Galois theory and polynomial equations, the driving conception was of a theory capable of unifying, by the study of symmetry, the whole area of ordinary differential equations.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] However, the hope that Lie theory would unify the entire field of ordinary differential equations was not fulfilled.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Symmetry methods for ODEs continue to be studied, but do not dominate the subject.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] There is a differential Galois theory, but it was developed by others, such as Picard and Vessiot, and it provides a theory of quadratures, the indefinite integrals required to express solutions.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Additional impetus to consider continuous groups came from ideas of Bernhard Riemann, on the foundations of geometry, and their further development in the hands of Klein.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The work of Killing, later refined and generalized by Élie Cartan, led to classification of semisimple Lie algebras, Cartan's theory of symmetric spaces, and Hermann Weyl's description of representations of compact and semisimple Lie groups using highest weights.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In 1900 David Hilbert challenged Lie theorists with his Fifth Problem presented at the International Congress of Mathematicians in Paris.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The theory of Lie groups was systematically reworked in modern mathematical language in a monograph by Claude Chevalley.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups are smooth differentiable manifolds and as such can be studied using differential calculus, in contrast with the case of more general topological groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] One of the key ideas in the theory of Lie groups is to replace the *global* object, the group, with its *local* or linearized version, which Lie himself called its "infinitesimal group" and which has since become known as its Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups play an enormous role in modern geometry, on several different levels.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Felix Klein argued in his Erlangen program that one can consider various "geometries" by specifying an appropriate transformation group that leaves certain geometric properties invariant.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This idea later led to the notion of a *G*-structure, where *G* is a Lie group of "local" symmetries of a manifold.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups (and their associated Lie algebras) play a major role in modern physics, with the Lie group typically playing the role of a symmetry of a physical system.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Here, the representations of the Lie group (or of its Lie algebra) are especially important.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Representation theory is used extensively in particle physics.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Groups whose representations are of particular importance include the rotation group SO(3) (or its double cover SU(2)), the special unitary group SU(3) and the Poincaré group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] On a "global" level, whenever a Lie group acts on a geometric object, such as a Riemannian or a symplectic manifold, this action provides a measure of rigidity and yields a rich algebraic structure.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The presence of continuous symmetries expressed via a Lie group action on a manifold places strong constraints on its geometry and facilitates analysis on the manifold.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Linear actions of Lie groups are especially important, and are studied in representation theory.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In the 1940s–1950s, Ellis Kolchin, Armand Borel, and Claude Chevalley realised that many foundational results concerning Lie groups can be developed completely algebraically, giving rise to the theory of algebraic groups defined over an arbitrary field.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This insight opened new possibilities in pure algebra, by providing a uniform construction for most finite simple groups, as well as in algebraic geometry.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The theory of automorphic forms, an important branch of modern number theory, deals extensively with analogues of Lie groups over adele rings; *p*-adic Lie groups play an important role, via their connections with Galois representations in number theory.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] A **real Lie group** is a group that is also a finite-dimensional real smooth manifold, in which the group operations of multiplication and inversion are smooth maps.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] means that $\mu$ is a smooth mapping of the product manifold $G\times G$ into G .
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] be a smooth mapping of the product manifold into G .
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] We now present an example of a group with an uncountable number of elements that is not a Lie group under a certain topology.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] with $a\in \mathbb {R} \setminus \mathbb {Q}$ a *fixed* irrational number, is a subgroup of the torus $\mathbb {T} ^{2}$ that is not a Lie group when given the subspace topology.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] If we take any small neighborhood U of a point h in ⁠ H ⁠, for example, the portion of H in U is disconnected.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The group H winds repeatedly around the torus without ever reaching a previous point of the spiral and thus forms a dense subgroup of ⁠ $\mathbb {T} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The group H can, however, be given a different topology, in which the distance between two points $h_{1},h_{2}\in H$ is defined as the length of the shortest path *in the group* H joining $h_{1}$ to ⁠ $h_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In this topology, H is identified homeomorphically with the real line by identifying each element with the number $\theta$ in the definition of ⁠ H ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] With this topology, H is just the group of real numbers under addition and is therefore a Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The group H is an example of a "Lie subgroup" of a Lie group that is not closed.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] See the discussion below of Lie subgroups in the section on basic concepts.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Let $\operatorname {GL} (n,\mathbb {C} )$ denote the group of $n\times n$ invertible matrices with entries in ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Restricting attention to matrix Lie groups simplifies the definition of the Lie algebra and the exponential map.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The following are standard examples of matrix Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] All of the preceding examples fall under the heading of the classical groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] A **complex Lie group** is defined in the same way using complex manifolds rather than real ones (example: $\operatorname {SL} (2,\mathbb {C} )$ ), and holomorphic maps.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Similarly, using an alternate metric completion of ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠, one can define a ***p*-adic Lie group** over the *p*-adic numbers, a topological group which is also an analytic *p*-adic manifold, such that the group operations are analytic.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In particular, each point has a *p*-adic neighborhood.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Hilbert's fifth problem asked whether replacing differentiable manifolds with topological or analytic ones can yield new examples.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The answer to this question turned out to be negative: in 1952, Gleason, Montgomery and Zippin showed that if *G* is a topological manifold with continuous group operations, then there exists exactly one analytic structure on *G* which turns it into a Lie group (see also Hilbert–Smith conjecture).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] If the underlying manifold is allowed to be infinite-dimensional (for example, a Hilbert manifold), then one arrives at the notion of an infinite-dimensional Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] It is possible to define analogues of many Lie groups over finite fields, and these give most of the examples of finite simple groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The language of category theory provides a concise definition for Lie groups: a Lie group is a group object in the category of smooth manifolds.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This is important, because it allows generalization of the notion of a Lie group to Lie supergroups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This categorical point of view leads also to a different generalization of Lie groups, namely Lie groupoids, which are groupoid objects in the category of smooth manifolds with a further requirement.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] A Lie group can be defined as a (Hausdorff) topological group that, near the identity element, looks like a transformation group, with no reference to differentiable manifolds nor topological manifolds.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Precisely, a *Lie group* is defined as a topological group that (1) is locally isomorphic near the identities to a matrix Lie group, a closed subgroup of $\operatorname {GL} (n,\mathbb {C} )$ and (2) has at most countably many connected components.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Conversely, let G be a topological group that is a Lie group in the above topological sense and choose a matrix Lie group $G'$ that is locally isomorphic to ⁠ G ⁠ around the respective identities.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Then, by a version of the closed subgroup theorem, $G'$ is a real-analytic manifold and then, through the local isomorphism, *G* acquires a structure of a manifold near the identity element.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] One then shows that the group law on *G* can be given by formal power series; so the group operations are real-analytic and G itself is a real-analytic manifold.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The topological definition implies the statement that if two Lie groups are isomorphic as topological groups, then they are isomorphic as Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In fact, it states the general principle that, to a large extent, *the topology of a Lie group* together with the group law determines the geometry of the group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups occur in abundance throughout mathematics and physics.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Matrix groups or algebraic groups are (roughly) groups of matrices (for example, orthogonal and symplectic groups), and these give most of the more common examples of Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The only connected Lie groups with dimension one are the real line $\mathbb {R}$ (with the group operation being addition) and the circle group $S^{1}$ of complex numbers with absolute value one (with the group operation being multiplication).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The $S^{1}$ group is often denoted as ⁠ $\operatorname {U} (1)$ ⁠, the group of $1\times 1$ unitary matrices.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In two dimensions, if we restrict attention to simply connected groups, then they are classified by their Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] There are (up to isomorphism) only two Lie algebras of dimension two.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The associated simply connected Lie groups are $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ (with the group operation being vector addition) and the affine group in dimension one, described in the previous subsection under "first examples".
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] To every Lie group we can associate a Lie algebra whose underlying vector space is the tangent space of the Lie group at the identity element and which completely captures the local structure of the group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Informally we can think of elements of the Lie algebra as elements of the group that are "infinitesimally close" to the identity, and the Lie bracket of the Lie algebra is related to the commutator of two such infinitesimal elements.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] If *G* is any group acting smoothly on the manifold *M*, then it acts on the vector fields, and the vector space of vector fields fixed by the group is closed under the Lie bracket and therefore also forms a Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] We apply this construction to the case when the manifold *M* is the underlying space of a Lie group *G*, with *G* acting on *G* = *M* by left translations *Lg*(*h*) = *gh*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This shows that the space of left invariant vector fields (vector fields satisfying *Lg***Xh* = *Xgh* for every *h* in *G*, where *Lg** denotes the differential of *Lg*) on a Lie group is a Lie algebra under the Lie bracket of vector fields.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Any tangent vector at the identity of a Lie group can be extended to a left invariant vector field by left translating the tangent vector to other points of the manifold.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Specifically, the left invariant extension of an element *v* of the tangent space at the identity is the vector field defined by *v*^*g* = *Lg***v*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is finite-dimensional and it has the same dimension as the manifold *G*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The Lie algebra of *G* determines *G* up to "local isomorphism", where two Lie groups are called **locally isomorphic** if they look the same near the identity element.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Problems about Lie groups are often solved by first solving the corresponding problem for the Lie algebras, and the result for groups then usually follows easily.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] For example, simple Lie groups are usually classified by first classifying the corresponding Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] We could also define a Lie algebra structure on *Te* using right invariant vector fields instead of left invariant vector fields.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This leads to the same Lie algebra, because the inverse map on *G* can be used to identify left invariant vector fields with right invariant vector fields, and acts as −1 on the tangent space *Te*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] on *G* × *G* sends (*e*, *e*) to *e*, so its derivative yields a bilinear operation on *TeG*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This bilinear operation is actually the zero map, but the second derivative, under the proper identification of tangent spaces, yields an operation that satisfies the axioms of a Lie bracket, and it is equal to twice the one defined through left-invariant vector fields.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] If *G* and *H* are Lie groups, then a Lie group homomorphism *f* : *G* → *H* is a smooth group homomorphism.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In the case of complex Lie groups, such a homomorphism is required to be a holomorphic map.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] However, these requirements are a bit stringent; every continuous homomorphism between real Lie groups turns out to be (real) analytic.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The composition of two Lie homomorphisms is again a homomorphism, and the class of all Lie groups, together with these morphisms, forms a category.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Moreover, every Lie group homomorphism induces a homomorphism between the corresponding Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Let $\phi :G\to H$ be a Lie group homomorphism and let $\phi _{*}$ be its derivative at the identity.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] which turns out to be a Lie algebra homomorphism (meaning that it is a linear map which preserves the Lie bracket).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In the language of category theory, we then have a covariant functor from the category of Lie groups to the category of Lie algebras which sends a Lie group to its Lie algebra and a Lie group homomorphism to its derivative at the identity.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Two Lie groups are called *isomorphic* if there exists a bijective homomorphism between them whose inverse is also a Lie group homomorphism.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Equivalently, it is a diffeomorphism which is also a group homomorphism.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Observe that, by the above, a continuous homomorphism from a Lie group G to a Lie group H is an isomorphism of Lie groups if and only if it is bijective.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Isomorphic Lie groups necessarily have isomorphic Lie algebras; it is then reasonable to ask how isomorphism classes of Lie groups relate to isomorphism classes of Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The first result in this direction is Lie's third theorem, which states that every finite-dimensional, real Lie algebra is the Lie algebra of some (linear) Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] One way to prove Lie's third theorem is to use Ado's theorem, which says every finite-dimensional real Lie algebra is isomorphic to a matrix Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Meanwhile, for every finite-dimensional matrix Lie algebra, there is a linear group (matrix Lie group) with this algebra as its Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] On the other hand, Lie groups with isomorphic Lie algebras need not be isomorphic.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Furthermore, this result remains true even if we assume the groups are connected.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] To put it differently, the *global* structure of a Lie group is not determined by its Lie algebra; for example, if *Z* is any discrete subgroup of the center of *G* then *G* and *G*/*Z* have the same Lie algebra (see the table of Lie groups for examples).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] An example of importance in physics are the groups SU(2) and SO(3).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] These two groups have isomorphic Lie algebras, but the groups themselves are not isomorphic, because SU(2) is simply connected but SO(3) is not.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] On the other hand, if we require that the Lie group be simply connected, then the global structure is determined by its Lie algebra: two simply connected Lie groups with isomorphic Lie algebras are isomorphic.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] A Lie group G is said to be **simply connected** if every loop in G can be shrunk continuously to a point in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie's third theorem says that every finite-dimensional real Lie algebra is the Lie algebra of a Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] It follows from Lie's third theorem and the preceding result that every finite-dimensional real Lie algebra is the Lie algebra of a *unique* simply connected Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] An example of a simply connected group is the special unitary group SU(2), which as a manifold is the 3-sphere.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The rotation group SO(3), on the other hand, is not simply connected.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] (See *Topology of SO(3)*.) The failure of SO(3) to be simply connected is intimately connected to the distinction between integer spin and half-integer spin in quantum mechanics.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Other examples of simply connected Lie groups include the special unitary group SU(n), the spin group (double cover of rotation group) Spin(*n*) for ⁠ $n\geq 3$ ⁠, and the compact symplectic group Sp(n).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Methods for determining whether a Lie group is simply connected or not are discussed in the article on fundamental groups of Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] If G is a closed subgroup of ⁠ $\mathrm {GL} (n;\mathbb {C} )$ ⁠, then the exponential map takes the Lie algebra of G into ⁠ G ⁠; thus, we have an exponential map for all matrix groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Every element of G that is sufficiently close to the identity is the exponential of a matrix in the Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The definition above is easy to use, but it is not defined for Lie groups that are not matrix groups, and it is not clear that the exponential map of a Lie group does not depend on its representation as a matrix group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] We can solve both problems using a more abstract definition of the exponential map that works for all Lie groups, as follows.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] For each vector X in the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ of G (i.e., the tangent space to G at the identity), one proves that there is a unique one-parameter subgroup $c:\mathbb {R} \rightarrow G$ such that ⁠ $c'(0)=X$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The operation on the right hand side is the group multiplication in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This is called the **exponential map**, and it maps the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ into the Lie group ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] It provides a diffeomorphism between a neighborhood of 0 in ${\mathfrak {g}}$ and a neighborhood of e in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Because the exponential map is surjective on some neighbourhood N of ⁠ e ⁠, it is common to call elements of the Lie algebra **infinitesimal generators** of the group ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The subgroup of G generated by N is the identity component of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] where the omitted terms are known and involve Lie brackets of four or more elements.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In case X and Y commute, this formula reduces to the familiar exponential law ⁠ $\exp(X)\exp(Y)=\exp(X+Y)$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The exponential map relates Lie group homomorphisms.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The exponential map from the Lie algebra to the Lie group is not always onto, even if the group is connected (though it does map onto the Lie group for connected groups that are either compact or nilpotent).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] For example, the exponential map of SL(2, **R**) is not surjective.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Also, the exponential map is neither surjective nor injective for infinite-dimensional (see below) Lie groups modelled on *C*∞ Fréchet space, even from arbitrary small neighborhood of 0 to corresponding neighborhood of 1.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] A **Lie subgroup** H of a Lie group G is a Lie group that is a subset of G and such that the inclusion map from H to G is an injective immersion and group homomorphism.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] According to Cartan's theorem, a closed subgroup of G admits a unique smooth structure which makes it an embedded Lie subgroup of G —i.e. a Lie subgroup such that the inclusion map is a smooth embedding.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Examples of non-closed subgroups are plentiful; for example take G to be a torus of dimension 2 or greater, and let H be a one-parameter subgroup of *irrational slope*, i.e. one that winds around in *G*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Then there is a Lie group homomorphism $\varphi :\mathbb {R} \to G$ with ⁠ $\mathrm {im} (\varphi )=H$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The closure of H will be a sub-torus in ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The exponential map gives a one-to-one correspondence between the connected Lie subgroups of a connected Lie group G and the subalgebras of the Lie algebra of ⁠ G ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Typically, the subgroup corresponding to a subalgebra is not a closed subgroup.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] There is no criterion solely based on the structure of G which determines which subalgebras correspond to closed subgroups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] One important aspect of the study of Lie groups is their representations, that is, the way they can act (linearly) on vector spaces.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In physics, Lie groups often encode the symmetries of a physical system.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The way one makes use of this symmetry to help analyze the system is often through representation theory.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Consider, for example, the time-independent Schrödinger equation in quantum mechanics, ⁠ ${\hat {H}}\psi =E\psi$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Assume the system in question has the rotation group SO(3) as a symmetry, meaning that the Hamiltonian operator ${\hat {H}}$ commutes with the action of SO(3) on the wave function ⁠ $\psi$ ⁠.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] (One important example of such a system is the hydrogen atom, which has a spherically symmetric potential.) This assumption does not necessarily mean that the solutions $\psi$ are rotationally invariant functions.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Rather, it means that the *space* of solutions to ${\hat {H}}\psi =E\psi$ is invariant under rotations (for each fixed value of E ).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This space, therefore, constitutes a representation of SO(3).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] These representations have been classified and the classification leads to a substantial simplification of the problem, essentially converting a three-dimensional partial differential equation to a one-dimensional ordinary differential equation.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The case of a connected compact Lie group *K* (including the just-mentioned case of SO(3)) is particularly tractable.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In that case, every finite-dimensional representation of *K* decomposes as a direct sum of irreducible representations.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The irreducible representations, in turn, were classified by Hermann Weyl.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The classification is in terms of the "highest weight" of the representation.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The classification is closely related to the classification of representations of a semisimple Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] One can also study (in general infinite-dimensional) unitary representations of an arbitrary Lie group (not necessarily compact).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] For example, it is possible to give a relatively simple explicit description of the representations of the group SL(2, **R**) and the representations of the Poincaré group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups may be thought of as smoothly varying families of symmetries.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Examples of symmetries include rotation about an axis.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] What must be understood is the nature of 'small' transformations, for example, rotations through tiny angles, that link nearby transformations.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The mathematical object capturing this structure is called a Lie algebra (Lie himself called them "infinitesimal groups").
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] It can be defined because Lie groups are smooth manifolds, so have tangent spaces at each point.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The Lie algebra of any compact Lie group (very roughly: one for which the symmetries form a bounded set) can be decomposed as a direct sum of an abelian Lie algebra and some number of simple ones.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The structure of an abelian Lie algebra is mathematically uninteresting (since the Lie bracket is identically zero); the interest is in the simple summands.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Hence the question arises: what are the simple Lie algebras of compact groups?
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] It turns out that they mostly fall into four infinite families, the "classical Lie algebras" A*n*, B*n*, C*n* and D*n*, which have simple descriptions in terms of symmetries of Euclidean space.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] But there are also just five "exceptional Lie algebras" that do not fall into any of these families.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups are classified according to their algebraic properties (simple, semisimple, solvable, nilpotent, abelian), their connectedness (connected or simply connected) and their compactness.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] A first key result is the Levi decomposition, which says that every simply connected Lie group is the semidirect product of a solvable normal subgroup and a semisimple subgroup.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The identity component of any Lie group is an open normal subgroup, and the quotient group is a discrete group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The universal cover of any connected Lie group is a simply connected Lie group, and conversely any connected Lie group is a quotient of a simply connected Lie group by a discrete normal subgroup of the center.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Any Lie group *G* can be decomposed into discrete, simple, and abelian groups in a canonical way as follows.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] /1 is nilpotent, and therefore its ascending central series has all quotients abelian.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] This can be used to reduce some problems about Lie groups (such as finding their unitary representations) to the same problems for connected simple groups and nilpotent and solvable subgroups of smaller dimension.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Lie groups are often defined to be finite-dimensional, but there are many groups that resemble Lie groups, except for being infinite-dimensional.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The simplest way to define infinite-dimensional Lie groups is to model them locally on Banach spaces (as opposed to Euclidean space in the finite-dimensional case), and in this case much of the basic theory is similar to that of finite-dimensional Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] However this is inadequate for many applications, because many natural examples of infinite-dimensional Lie groups are not Banach manifolds.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] Instead one needs to define Lie groups modeled on more general locally convex topological vector spaces.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] In this case the relation between the Lie algebra and the Lie group becomes rather subtle, and several results about finite-dimensional Lie groups no longer hold.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] The literature is not entirely uniform in its terminology as to exactly which properties of infinite-dimensional groups qualify the group for the prefix *Lie* in *Lie group*.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] On the Lie algebra side of affairs, things are simpler since the qualifying criteria for the prefix *Lie* in *Lie algebra* are purely algebraic.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] For example, an infinite-dimensional Lie algebra may or may not have a corresponding Lie group.
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] That is, there may be a group corresponding to the Lie algebra, but it might not be nice enough to be called a Lie group, or the connection between the group and the Lie algebra might not be nice enough (for example, failure of the exponential map to be onto a neighborhood of the identity).
[src:lie-groups/lie-group] It is the "nice enough" that is not universally defined.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] In the mathematical theory of compact Lie groups a special role is played by torus subgroups, in particular by the **maximal torus** subgroups.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] A **torus** in a compact Lie group *G* is a compact, connected, abelian Lie subgroup of *G* (and therefore isomorphic to the standard torus **T***n*).
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] A **maximal torus** is one which is maximal among such subgroups.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] That is, *T* is a maximal torus if for any torus *T*′ containing *T* we have *T* = *T*′.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Every torus is contained in a maximal torus simply by dimensional considerations.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] A noncompact Lie group need not have any nontrivial tori (e.g.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The dimension of a maximal torus in *G* is called the **rank** of *G*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The rank is well-defined since all maximal tori turn out to be conjugate.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] For semisimple groups the rank is equal to the number of nodes in the associated Dynkin diagram.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The unitary group U(*n*) has as a maximal torus the subgroup of all diagonal matrices.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] A maximal torus in the special orthogonal group SO(2*n*) is given by the set of all simultaneous rotations in any fixed choice of *n* pairwise orthogonal planes (i.e., two dimensional vector spaces).
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Concretely, one maximal torus consists of all block-diagonal matrices with $2\times 2$ diagonal blocks, where each diagonal block is a rotation matrix.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] This is also a maximal torus in the group SO(2*n*+1) where the action fixes the remaining direction.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] For example, in the rotation group SO(3) the maximal tori are given by rotations about a fixed axis.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The symplectic group Sp(*n*) has rank *n*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] A maximal torus is given by the set of all diagonal matrices whose entries all lie in a fixed complex subalgebra of **H**.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Let *G* be a compact, connected Lie group and let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ be the Lie algebra of *G*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] If *T* is a maximal torus in a compact Lie group *G*, one can define a root system as follows.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The roots are the weights for the adjoint action of *T* on the complexified Lie algebra of *G*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] To be more explicit, let ${\mathfrak {t}}$ denote the Lie algebra of *T*, let ${\mathfrak {g}}$ denote the Lie algebra of G , and let ${\mathfrak {g}}_{\mathbb {C} }:={\mathfrak {g}}\oplus i{\mathfrak {g}}$ denote the complexification of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Here $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ is a fixed inner product on ${\mathfrak {g}}$ that is invariant under the adjoint action of connected compact Lie groups.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The root system, as a subset of the Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {t}}$ of *T*, has all the usual properties of a root system, except that the roots may not span ${\mathfrak {t}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The root system is a key tool in understanding the classification and representation theory of *G*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Given a torus *T* (not necessarily maximal), the Weyl group of *G* with respect to *T* can be defined as the normalizer of *T* modulo the centralizer of *T*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Fix a maximal torus $T=T_{0}$ in *G;* then the corresponding Weyl group is called the Weyl group of *G* (it depends up to isomorphism on the choice of *T*).
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The first two major results about the Weyl group are as follows.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] We now list some consequences of these main results.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The representation theory of *G* is essentially determined by *T* and *W*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] As an example, consider the case $G=SU(n)$ with T being the diagonal subgroup of G .
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Then $x\in G$ belongs to $N(T)$ if and only if x maps each standard basis element $e_{i}$ to a multiple of some other standard basis element $e_{j}$ , that is, if and only if x permutes the standard basis elements, up to multiplication by some constants.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] The Weyl group in this case is then the permutation group on n elements.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Suppose *f* is a continuous function on *G*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] where $d[y]$ is the normalized volume measure on the quotient manifold $G/T$ and $dt$ is the normalized Haar measure on *T*.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Here Δ is given by the Weyl denominator formula and $|W|$ is the order of the Weyl group.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] An important special case of this result occurs when *f* is a class function, that is, a function invariant under conjugation.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Consider as an example the case $G=SU(2)$ , with T being the diagonal subgroup.
[src:lie-groups/maximal-torus] Here $|W|=2$ , the normalized Haar measure on T is ${\frac {d\theta }{2\pi }}$ , and $\mathrm {diag} \left(e^{i\theta },e^{-i\theta }\right)$ denotes the diagonal matrix with diagonal entries $e^{i\theta }$ and $e^{-i\theta }$ .
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] from the real line $\mathbb {R}$ (as an additive group) to some other topological group G .
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] If $\varphi$ is injective then $\varphi (\mathbb {R} )$ , the image, will be a subgroup of G that is isomorphic to $\mathbb {R}$ as an additive group.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Despite its name, "a one-parameter group" is not actually a group, but a homomorphism *between* groups.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] One-parameter groups were introduced by Sophus Lie in 1893 to define infinitesimal transformations.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] According to Lie, an *infinitesimal transformation* is an infinitely small transformation of the one-parameter group that it generates.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] It is these infinitesimal transformations that generate a Lie algebra that is used to describe a Lie group of any dimension.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The action of a one-parameter group on a set is known as a flow.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] A smooth vector field on a manifold, at a point, induces a *local flow* - a one parameter group of local diffeomorphisms, sending points along integral curves of the vector field.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The local flow of a vector field is used to define the Lie derivative of tensor fields along the vector field.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] In Lie theory, one-parameter groups correspond to one-dimensional subspaces of the associated Lie algebra.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The Lie group–Lie algebra correspondence is the basis of a science begun by Sophus Lie in the 1890s.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Another important case is seen in functional analysis, with G being the group of unitary operators on a Hilbert space.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] See Stone's theorem on one-parameter unitary groups.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] In physics, one-parameter groups describe dynamical systems.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Furthermore, whenever a system of physical laws admits a one-parameter group of differentiable symmetries, then there is a conserved quantity, by Noether's theorem.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] In the study of spacetime the use of the unit hyperbola to calibrate spatio-temporal measurements has become common since Hermann Minkowski discussed it in 1908.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The principle of relativity was reduced to arbitrariness of which diameter of the unit hyperbola was used to determine a world-line.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Using the parametrization of the hyperbola with hyperbolic angle, the theory of special relativity provided a calculus of relative motion with the one-parameter group indexed by rapidity.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The *rapidity* replaces the *velocity* in kinematics and dynamics of relativity theory.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Since rapidity is unbounded, the one-parameter group it stands upon is non-compact.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The rapidity concept was introduced by E.T.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Whittaker in 1910, and named by Alfred Robb the next year.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] The rapidity parameter amounts to the length of a hyperbolic versor, a concept of the nineteenth century.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Mathematical physicists James Cockle, William Kingdon Clifford, and Alexander Macfarlane had all employed in their writings an equivalent mapping of the Cartesian plane by operator $(\cosh {a}+r\sinh {a})$ , where a is the hyperbolic angle and $r^{2}=+1$ .
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] An important example in the theory of Lie groups arises when G is taken to be $\mathrm {GL} (n;\mathbb {C} )$ , the group of invertible $n\times n$ matrices with complex entries.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] It follows from this result that $\varphi$ is differentiable, even though this was not an assumption of the theorem.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] This result can be used, for example, to show that any continuous homomorphism between matrix Lie groups is smooth.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] A technical complication is that $\varphi (\mathbb {R} )$ as a subspace of G may carry a topology that is coarser than that on $\mathbb {R}$ ; this may happen in cases where $\varphi$ is injective.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] Think for example of the case where G is a torus T , and $\varphi$ is constructed by winding a straight line round T at an irrational slope.
[src:lie-groups/one-parameter-group] In that case the induced topology may not be the standard one of the real line.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In mathematics, a **root system** is a configuration of vectors in a Euclidean space satisfying certain geometrical properties.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The concept is fundamental in the theory of Lie groups and Lie algebras, especially the classification and representation theory of semisimple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Since Lie groups (and some analogues such as algebraic groups) and Lie algebras have become important in many parts of mathematics during the twentieth century, the apparently special nature of root systems belies the number of areas in which they are applied.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Further, the classification scheme for root systems, by Dynkin diagrams, occurs in parts of mathematics with no overt connection to Lie theory (such as singularity theory).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Finally, root systems are important for their own sake, as in spectral graph theory.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] As a first example, consider the six vectors in 2-dimensional Euclidean space, **R**2, as shown in the image at the right; call them **roots**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If you consider the line perpendicular to any root, say *β*, then the reflection of **R**2 in that line sends any other root, say *α*, to another root.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Moreover, the root to which it is sent equals *α* + *nβ*, where *n* is an integer (in this case, *n* equals 1).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] These six vectors satisfy the following definition, and therefore they form a root system; this one is known as *A*2.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Let *E* be a finite-dimensional Euclidean vector space, with the standard Euclidean inner product denoted by $(\cdot ,\cdot )$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The only scalar multiples of a root $\alpha \in \Phi$ that belong to $\Phi$ are $\alpha$ itself and $-\alpha$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] For every root $\alpha \in \Phi$ , the set $\Phi$ is closed under reflection through the hyperplane perpendicular to $\alpha$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] (**Integrality**) If $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are roots in $\Phi$ , then the projection of $\beta$ onto the line through $\alpha$ is an *integer or half-integer* multiple of $\alpha$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] For any two roots $\alpha ,\beta \in \Phi$ , the number $\langle \beta ,\alpha \rangle :=2{\frac {(\alpha ,\beta )}{(\alpha ,\alpha )}}$ is an integer.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Some authors only include conditions 1–3 in the definition of a root system.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In this context, a root system that also satisfies the integrality condition is known as a **crystallographic root system**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Other authors omit condition 2; then they call root systems satisfying condition 2 **reduced**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In this article, all root systems are assumed to be reduced and crystallographic.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In view of property 3, the integrality condition is equivalent to stating that *β* and its reflection *σ**α*(*β*) differ by an integer multiple of *α*.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Note that the operator $\langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle \colon \Phi \times \Phi \to \mathbb {Z}$ defined by property 4 is not an inner product.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] It is not necessarily symmetric and is linear only in the first argument.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The **rank** of a root system Φ is the dimension of *E*.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Two root systems may be combined by regarding the Euclidean spaces they span as mutually orthogonal subspaces of a common Euclidean space.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] A root system which does not arise from such a combination, such as the systems *A*2, *B*2, and *G*2 pictured to the right, is said to be **irreducible**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Two root systems (*E*1, Φ1) and (*E*2, Φ2) are called **isomorphic** if there is an invertible linear transformation *E*1 → *E*2 which sends Φ1 to Φ2 such that for each pair of roots, the number $\langle x,y\rangle$ is preserved.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The **root lattice** of a root system Φ is the **Z**-submodule of *E* generated by Φ.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The group of isometries of *E* generated by reflections through hyperplanes associated to the roots of Φ is called the Weyl group of Φ.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] As it acts faithfully on the finite set Φ, the Weyl group is always finite.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The reflection planes are the hyperplanes perpendicular to the roots, indicated for $A_{2}$ by dashed lines in the figure below.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The Weyl group is the symmetry group of an equilateral triangle, which has six elements.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In this case, the Weyl group is not the full symmetry group of the root system (e.g., a 60-degree rotation is a symmetry of the root system but not an element of the Weyl group).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] There is only one root system of rank 1, consisting of two nonzero vectors $\{\alpha ,-\alpha \}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In rank 2 there are four possibilities, corresponding to $\sigma _{\alpha }(\beta )=\beta +n\alpha$ , where $n=0,1,2,3$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The figure at right shows these possibilities, but with some redundancies: $A_{1}\times A_{1}$ is isomorphic to $D_{2}$ and $B_{2}$ is isomorphic to $C_{2}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Note that a root system is not determined by the lattice that it generates: $A_{1}\times A_{1}$ and $B_{2}$ both generate a square lattice while $A_{2}$ and $G_{2}$ both generate a hexagonal lattice.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Whenever Φ is a root system in *E*, and *S* is a subspace of *E* spanned by Ψ = Φ ∩ *S*, then Ψ is a root system in *S*.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus, the exhaustive list of four root systems of rank 2 shows the geometric possibilities for any two roots chosen from a root system of arbitrary rank.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a complex semisimple Lie algebra and ${\mathfrak {h}}$ is a Cartan subalgebra, we can construct a root system as follows.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] We say that $\alpha \in {\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ is a **root** of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ relative to ${\mathfrak {h}}$ if $\alpha \neq 0$ and there exists some $X\neq 0\in {\mathfrak {g}}$ such that $[H,X]=\alpha (H)X$ for all $H\in {\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] One can show that there is an inner product for which the set of roots forms a root system.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The root system of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ is a fundamental tool for analyzing the structure of ${\mathfrak {g}}$ and classifying its representations.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The concept of a root system was originally introduced by Wilhelm Killing around 1889 (in German, *Wurzelsystem*).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] He used them in his attempt to classify all simple Lie algebras over the field of complex numbers.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] (Killing originally made a mistake in the classification, listing two exceptional rank 4 root systems, when in fact there is only one, now known as F4.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Killing investigated the structure of a Lie algebra L by considering what is now called a Cartan subalgebra ${\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Then he studied the roots of the characteristic polynomial $\det(\operatorname {ad} _{L}x-t)$ , where $x\in {\mathfrak {h}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Here a *root* is considered as a function of ${\mathfrak {h}}$ , or indeed as an element of the dual vector space ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] This set of roots forms a root system inside ${\mathfrak {h}}^{*}$ , as defined above, where the inner product is the Killing form.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The cosine of the angle between two roots is constrained to be one-half of the square root of a positive integer.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Condition 2 says that no scalar multiples of *α* other than 1 and −1 can be roots, so 0 or 180°, which would correspond to 2*α* or −2*α*, are out.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The diagram at right shows that an angle of 60° or 120° corresponds to roots of equal length, while an angle of 45° or 135° corresponds to a length ratio of ${\sqrt {2}}$ and an angle of 30° or 150° corresponds to a length ratio of ${\sqrt {3}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In summary, here are the only possibilities for each pair of roots.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Given a root system $\Phi$ we can always choose (in many ways) a set of **positive roots**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If a set of positive roots $\Phi ^{+}$ is chosen, elements of $-\Phi ^{+}$ are called **negative roots**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] A set of positive roots may be constructed by choosing a hyperplane V not containing any root and setting $\Phi ^{+}$ to be all the roots lying on a fixed side of V .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Furthermore, every set of positive roots arises in this way.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] An element of $\Phi ^{+}$ is called a **simple root** (also *fundamental root*) if it cannot be written as the sum of two elements of $\Phi ^{+}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] For each root system $\Phi$ there are many different choices of the set of positive roots—or, equivalently, of the simple roots—but any two sets of positive roots differ by the action of the Weyl group.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The set of coroots also forms a root system Φ∨ in *E*, called the **dual root system** (or sometimes *inverse root system*).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] By direct calculation, α∨∨ = α, so that Φ is the dual root system of Φ∨.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The lattice in *E* spanned by Φ∨ is called the *coroot lattice*.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If Δ is a set of simple roots for Φ, then Δ∨ is a set of simple roots for Φ∨.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In the classification described below, the root systems of type $A_{n}$ and $D_{n}$ along with the exceptional root systems $E_{6},E_{7},E_{8},F_{4},G_{2}$ are all self-dual, meaning that the dual root system is isomorphic to the original root system.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] By contrast, the $B_{n}$ and $C_{n}$ root systems are dual to one another, but not isomorphic (except when $n=2$ ).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The set of integral elements is called the **weight lattice** associated to the given root system.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] This term comes from the representation theory of semisimple Lie algebras, where the integral elements form the possible weights of finite-dimensional representations.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The definition of a root system guarantees that the roots themselves are integral elements.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus, every integer linear combination of roots is also integral.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In most cases, however, there will be integral elements that are not integer combinations of roots.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] That is to say, in general the weight lattice does not coincide with the root lattice.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] A root system is irreducible if it cannot be partitioned into the union of two proper subsets $\Phi =\Phi _{1}\cup \Phi _{2}$ , such that $(\alpha ,\beta )=0$ for all $\alpha \in \Phi _{1}$ and $\beta \in \Phi _{2}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Irreducible root systems correspond to certain graphs, the **Dynkin diagrams** named after Eugene Dynkin.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The classification of these graphs is a simple matter of combinatorics, and induces a classification of irreducible root systems.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Given a root system, select a set Δ of simple roots as in the preceding section.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The vertices of the associated Dynkin diagram correspond to the roots in Δ.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Edges are drawn between vertices as follows, according to the angles.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The term "directed edge" means that double and triple edges are marked with an arrow pointing toward the shorter vector.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Note that by the elementary properties of roots noted above, the rules for creating the Dynkin diagram can also be described as follows.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] No edge if the roots are orthogonal; for nonorthogonal roots, a single, double, or triple edge according to whether the length ratio of the longer to shorter is 1, ${\sqrt {2}}$ , ${\sqrt {3}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In the case of the $G_{2}$ root system for example, there are two simple roots at an angle of 150 degrees (with a length ratio of ${\sqrt {3}}$ ).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus, the Dynkin diagram has two vertices joined by a triple edge, with an arrow pointing from the vertex associated to the longer root to the other vertex.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Although a given root system has more than one possible set of simple roots, the Weyl group acts transitively on such choices.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Consequently, the Dynkin diagram is independent of the choice of simple roots; it is determined by the root system itself.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Conversely, given two root systems with the same Dynkin diagram, one can match up roots, starting with the roots in the base, and show that the systems are in fact the same.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus the problem of classifying root systems reduces to the problem of classifying possible Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] A root systems is irreducible if and only if its Dynkin diagram is connected.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The possible connected diagrams are as indicated in the figure.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The subscripts indicate the number of vertices in the diagram (and hence the rank of the corresponding irreducible root system).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If $\Phi$ is a root system, the Dynkin diagram for the dual root system $\Phi ^{\vee }$ is obtained from the Dynkin diagram of $\Phi$ by keeping all the same vertices and edges, but reversing the directions of all arrows.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus, we can see from their Dynkin diagrams that $B_{n}$ and $C_{n}$ are dual to each other.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If $\Phi \subset E$ is a root system, we may consider the hyperplane perpendicular to each root $\alpha$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Recall that $\sigma _{\alpha }$ denotes the reflection about the hyperplane and that the Weyl group is the group of transformations of E generated by all the $\sigma _{\alpha }$ 's.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The complement of the set of hyperplanes is disconnected, and each connected component is called a **Weyl chamber**.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If we have fixed a particular set Δ of simple roots, we may define the **fundamental Weyl chamber** associated to Δ as the set of points $v\in E$ such that $(\alpha ,v)>0$ for all $\alpha \in \Delta$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Since the reflections $\sigma _{\alpha },\,\alpha \in \Phi$ preserve $\Phi$ , they also preserve the set of hyperplanes perpendicular to the roots.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus, each Weyl group element permutes the Weyl chambers.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The figure illustrates the case of the $A_{2}$ root system.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The "hyperplanes" (in this case, one dimensional) orthogonal to the roots are indicated by dashed lines.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The six 60-degree sectors are the Weyl chambers and the shaded region is the fundamental Weyl chamber associated to the indicated base.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] : The Weyl group acts freely and transitively on the Weyl chambers.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Thus, the order of the Weyl group is equal to the number of Weyl chambers.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In the $A_{2}$ case, for example, the Weyl group has six elements and there are six Weyl chambers.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In each case, the roots are non-zero weights of the adjoint representation.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] We now give a brief indication of how irreducible root systems classify simple Lie algebras over $\mathbb {C}$ , following the arguments in Humphreys.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] A preliminary result says that a semisimple Lie algebra is simple if and only if the associated root system is irreducible.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] We thus restrict attention to irreducible root systems and simple Lie algebras.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] For connections between the exceptional root systems and their Lie groups and Lie algebras see E8, E7, E6, F4, and G2.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Irreducible root systems are named according to their corresponding connected Dynkin diagrams.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] There are four infinite families (A*n*, B*n*, C*n*, and D*n*, called the **classical root systems**) and five exceptional cases (the **exceptional root systems**).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The subscript indicates the rank of the root system.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In an irreducible root system there can be at most two values for the length (*α*, *α*)1/2, corresponding to **short** and **long** roots.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] If all roots have the same length they are taken to be long by definition and the root system is said to be **simply laced**; this occurs in the cases A, D and E.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Any two roots of the same length lie in the same orbit of the Weyl group.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In the non-simply laced cases B, C, G and F, the root lattice is spanned by the short roots and the long roots span a sublattice, invariant under the Weyl group, equal to *r*2/2 times the coroot lattice, where *r* is the length of a long root.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In the adjacent table, |Φ<| denotes the number of short roots, I denotes the index in the root lattice of the sublattice generated by long roots, *D* denotes the determinant of the Cartan matrix, and |*W*| denotes the order of the Weyl group.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Let *E* be the subspace of **R***n*+1 for which the coordinates sum to 0, and let Φ be the set of vectors in *E* of length √2 and which are *integer vectors,* i.e. have integer coordinates in **R***n*+1.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Such a vector must have all but two coordinates equal to 0, one coordinate equal to 1, and one equal to −1, so there are *n*2 + *n* roots in all.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] One choice of simple roots expressed in the standard basis is **α***i* = **e***i* − **e***i*+1 for 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *n*.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The reflection *σ**i* through the hyperplane perpendicular to **α***i* is the same as permutation of the adjacent *i*th and (*i* + 1)th coordinates.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Such transpositions generate the full permutation group.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *A**n* root lattice – that is, the lattice generated by the *A**n* roots – is most easily described as the set of integer vectors in **R***n*+1 whose components sum to zero.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *A*2 root lattice is the vertex arrangement of the triangular tiling.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *A*3 root lattice is known to crystallographers as the face-centered cubic (or cubic close packed) lattice.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] It is the vertex arrangement of the tetrahedral-octahedral honeycomb.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *A*3 root system (as well as the other rank-three root systems) may be modeled in the Zometool construction set.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] In general, the *A**n* root lattice is the vertex arrangement of the *n*-dimensional simplicial honeycomb.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Let *E* = **R***n*, and let Φ consist of all integer vectors in *E* of length 1 or √2.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The reflection *σ**n* through the hyperplane perpendicular to the short root **α***n* is of course simply negation of the *n*th coordinate.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *B**n* root lattice—that is, the lattice generated by the *B**n* roots—consists of all integer vectors.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Let *E* = **R***n*, and let Φ consist of all integer vectors in *E* of length √2 together with all vectors of the form 2*λ*, where *λ* is an integer vector of length 1.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *C**n* root lattice—that is, the lattice generated by the *C**n* roots—consists of all integer vectors whose components sum to an even integer.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Let *E* = **R***n*, and let Φ consist of all integer vectors in *E* of length √2.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The total number of roots is 2*n*(*n* − 1).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Reflection through the hyperplane perpendicular to **α***n* is the same as transposing and negating the adjacent *n*-th and (*n* − 1)-th coordinates.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Any simple root and its reflection perpendicular to another simple root differ by a multiple of 0 or 1 of the second root, not by any greater multiple.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *D**n* root lattice – that is, the lattice generated by the *D**n* roots – consists of all integer vectors whose components sum to an even integer.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] This is the same as the *C**n* root lattice.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *D**n* roots are expressed as the vertices of a rectified *n*-orthoplex, Coxeter–Dynkin diagram: ....
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The 2*n*(*n* − 1) vertices exist in the middle of the edges of the *n*-orthoplex.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The set just listed is the set of vectors of length √2 in the E8 root lattice, also known simply as the E8 lattice or Γ8.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] 2. the sum of the eight coordinates is an even integer.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The lattices Γ8 and Γ'8 are isomorphic; one may pass from one to the other by changing the signs of any odd number of coordinates.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The lattice Γ8 is sometimes called the *even coordinate system* for *E*8 while the lattice Γ'8 is called the *odd coordinate system*.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] (Using ***β***3 would give an isomorphic result.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Since perpendicularity to ***α***1 means that the first two coordinates are equal, *E*7 is then the subset of *E*8 where the first two coordinates are equal, and similarly *E*6 is the subset of *E*8 where the first three coordinates are equal.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] Note that deleting ***α***1 and then ***α***2 gives sets of simple roots for *E*7 and *E*6.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] However, these sets of simple roots are in different *E*7 and *E*6 subspaces of *E*8 than the ones written above, since they are not orthogonal to ***α***1 or ***α***2.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] For *F*4, let *E* = **R**4, and let Φ denote the set of vectors α of length 1 or √2 such that the coordinates of 2α are all integers and are either all even or all odd.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] One choice of simple roots is: the choice of simple roots given above for *B*3, plus ${\textstyle {\boldsymbol {\alpha }}_{4}=-{\frac {1}{2}}\sum _{i=1}^{4}e_{i}}$ .
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *F*4 root lattice—that is, the lattice generated by the *F*4 root system—is the set of points in **R**4 such that either all the coordinates are integers or all the coordinates are half-integers (a mixture of integers and half-integers is not allowed).
[src:lie-groups/root-system] This lattice is isomorphic to the lattice of Hurwitz quaternions.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The root system *G*2 has 12 roots, which form the vertices of a hexagram.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The *G*2 root lattice—that is, the lattice generated by the *G*2 roots—is the same as the *A*2 root lattice.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The set of positive roots is naturally ordered by saying that $\alpha \leq \beta$ if and only if $\beta -\alpha$ is a nonnegative linear combination of simple roots.
[src:lie-groups/root-system] The Hasse graph is a visualization of the ordering of the root poset.
